As @Tilman already mentioned, transforming by `Matrix.getRotateInstance(angle, x, y)` rotates around the origin (0, 0) of the coordinate system (which usually is the lower left corner of a page) and then translates by (x, y).

You on the other hand likely want to rotate around a different point, probably around the center of the page (or the center of your watermark). You can rotate around an arbitrary point by enveloping the rotation between two translations that first move that desired center to the origin and afterwards back to its original position, i.e. for a rotation center at (tx, ty) do

```lang-java
cs.transform(Matrix.getTranslateInstance(tx, ty));
cs.transform(Matrix.getRotateInstance(angle, 0, 0));
cs.transform(Matrix.getTranslateInstance(-tx, -ty));
```

----

By the way, this technique has been used in the first option of [this answer](https://stackoverflow.com/a/40630514/1729265) on the topic of _rotating a PDF around its center_.

